<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 93 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Reclaiming income tax
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
My wife and I have established a discretionary trust, with our grandchildren
as the beneficiaries.
One of our sons works for an EU institution abroad and his children have
visited Britain only on holidays.
When they get income from the trust, can they claim back the income tax
already deducted from it, as their UK-resident cousins can do? If so, where
should their father apply for such repayment?
It appears that your grand-children are British citizens no matter where
they live. Thus, they are entitled to their annual personal allowance for
income tax.
It should be possible for them to claim back the tax deducted on payments
from the trustees. In order to do this, the trustees should supply the
children with a certificate showing tax deducted. This should be submitted
with a letter requesting a refund to Claims Branch, St John's House, Merton
Road, Bootle, Merseyside L69 9BP.
You will need to check the way in which the income distribution is taxed in
the country where the children are resident.
Reply by Barry Stillerman of accountant Stoy Hayward.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
