<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 93 / World Commodities Prices: Spices
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lack of offers from origins pushed prices for white pepper higher in the
latter part of this week, reports Man Producten. The next crop in Indonesia
 -the largest supplier of white pepper - is not due until July/August and
the existing stock is tightly controlled. So further price rises for whites
are likely. Imports into the US are running behind both 1992 and 1991.
Muntok whites traded at Dollars 2,700 a tonne for January delivery, while in
New York the ex-warehouse price was Dollars 3,100 a tonne. Brazilian
supplies were offered at about Dollars 2,600 a tonne, fob The black pepper
market reflected the steadiness of the whites. Brazilian prices were
stronger, with the limited quantities offered all absorbed. Renewed Russian
interest in India pepper has brightened the prospects for the new crop. The
harvest in Kerala is said to be delayed.
