<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 93 / Exchange withholds study on USM substitute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The London Stock Exchange has declined to release a report prepared by one
of its own working parties which recommends the creation of a separate
market for the trading of small company shares intended to replace the
Unlisted Securities Market.
After a long board meeting on Thursday, the exchange said it had decided
there was insufficient evidence of public support for the creation of a
so-called Enterprise Market, with its own management. That proposal has had
strong support from venture capitalists and stockbrokers specialising in the
shares of smaller companies.
Mr Andrew Beeson, chairman of stockbrokers Beeson Gregory and chairman of
the City Group for Smaller Companies (Cisco) - which had urged the creation
of the new market - said yesterday he was 'disappointed' at the Stock
Exchange move. While Cisco still preferred to see an Enterprise Market
operating as part of the London Stock Exchange, 'there will be venture
capitalists who will be prepared to spawn a new market,' he said.
The exchange, in announcing it was shelving the report - if only temporarily
 -acknowledged that it has not been seen as a promoter of small company
interests.
'There is a widespread perception that the needs of smaller enterprise
companies are not always adequately catered for,' the exchange said in a
statement. It added that it 'will consider whether changes in the exchange's
organisation or in regulatory arrangements are required to deliver the
necessary service'.
Earlier this year the Stock Exchange said it would close the USM, partly
because it was concerned that the distinctions between it and the main
official list of traded companies were too blurred. The exchange's Smaller
Companies Working Party, established last April, had recommended that the
new market be established and operate under the aegis of the Stock Exchange.
The working party had suggested that the Enterprise Market could
alternatively try to distinguish itself from the Stock Exchange's official
list of traded companies by lowering regulatory and reporting requirements
for companies whose shares trade there.
It had been intended that the working party's report would be released by
the Stock Exchange as a consultation document and that no planning would
occur until the comment period had expired. However, the board voted instead
to commission additional market research aimed at investigating the degree
of public support for a new exchange.
Privately, some Cisco members said the board's move may have been prompted
by fears of embarrassment if the new market failed to attract sufficient
support. 'They are saying that if we revamp the secondary market for a
second time and it doesn't work we will look really stupid,' one member
said.
Go-getters, Page 9
</TEXT>
