<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 93 / Lyell reinforces stance on Levitt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, yesterday again defended the
Serious Fraud Office's handling of the trial of Mr Roger Levitt.
He insisted prosecuting lawyers had not been told the businessman's
barristers intended to cite other cases where fraudsters received suspended
sentences before the SFO agreed to Mr Levitt's guilty plea.
The controversy of the plea bargain arose after Mr Levitt received a
180-hour community service order having admitted a single charge of
deceiving Fimbra, the Levitt Group's regulator - only one of a number of
charges the SFO had brought against him.
Controversy afterwards centred on whether the SFO was aware Mr Levitt might
receive a non-custodial sentence after making such a plea.
Yesterday Sir Nicholas said in a parliamentary answer that he had been told
by prosecution counsel that they had not been informed of any intention by
Mr Levitt's lawyers to use examples such as Mr Terry Ramsden, the former
Japanese-warrants dealer given a suspended sentence after admitting fraud,
during their plea-bargaining efforts.
However, earlier this week the trial judge, Mr Justice Laws, agreed that
transcripts of the plea-bargaining discussions could be made public.
In these it is disclosed that before the SFO accepted Mr Levitt's plea, his
barrister, Mr Jonathan Goldberg QC, sent a letter to Mr David Cocks, QC for
the SFO. It ended: 'If you are instructed to accept such a plea, I am
instructed to seek an indication from the judge on sentence and Mr Levitt
will then decide what to do.'
The attorney-general also enlarged on a previous statement to MPs when he
admitted that discussions over the possible plea might have taken place
before November 22 - the day Mr Levitt made his plea in front of the jury.
In an earlier parliamentary answer Sir Nicholas denied that the SFO
approached Mr Levitt about a possible plea before then. Yesterday he said
discussions may have taken place before, adding: 'I have been assured by
prosecuting counsel that although potential pleas may have been discussed on
a counsel-to-counsel basis no offers were made by the Crown to Mr Levitt.'
</TEXT>
