<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 93 / Fyodorov insists economic reformwill continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Boris Fyodorov, Russia's finance minister, yesterday told the Group of
Seven countries which have spearheaded aid to his country that, in spite of
the controversial results of the recent election, there would still be a
majority in favour of continuing reform.
At a meeting in Paris with senior G7 officials, the minister said he was
confident that when the final election results were in, there would be 'a
parliamentary majority in favour of economic reform', according to a French
official.
'The meeting did not take any decisions, and was not supposed to do so,'
said the official.
Mr Fyodorov and the International Monetary Fund officials were both quoted
as expressing satisfaction with their current negotiations on future western
aid.
Russia has already received half of a Dollars 3bn (Pounds 1.9bn) special
'facility for systemic transformation' and is now seeking to persuade the G7
and the IMF that it is sufficiently committed to economic reform to merit
the rest, and eventually a regular IMF standby credit.
Earlier this week, Mr Al Gore, the US vice president, criticised the IMF and
the governments on its board for being insufficiently sensitive to the
effect of harsh budget cuts on individual Russians.
But, according to the French official, this was not echoed in yesterday's
meeting in Paris where the US was represented by Mr Larry Summers, the US
Treasury under-secretary.
The International Monetary Fund said yesterday it approved about Dollars
103m in credits for Moldova to help the country stabilise and reform its
economy, Reuter reports from Washington.
Despite declining economic activity and rising inflation, the former Soviet
republic made significant progress reforming its economy this year,
launching a privatisation programme, introducing a new currency and moving
to rein in the government budget deficit, the IMF said.
</TEXT>
