<DATE>931217
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Markets Report: D-Mark broadly firmer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bundesbank's decision yesterday to leave official interest rates
unchanged bolstered the D-Mark against the US dollar and most European
currencies, writes Conner Middelmann.
At its last meeting of the year, the Bundesbank's central bank council held
its 5.75 per cent discount rate and 6.75 per cent Lombard rate steady. This
disappointed many dealers, who had hoped for another rate cut before the
year-end, in spite of the Bundesbank's recent reminder that it had set
fixed-rate securities repurchase agreements until January 5 to quell
speculation about a cut in interest rates.
But even before the Bundesbank said it was leaving rates unchanged, the
dollar slid on the announcement that German M3 money supply had grown by an
annualised 7.2 per cent in the year to November, up from 6.9 per cent in
October and well above forecasts for a 6.7 per cent rate. This not only
dampened hopes that M3 would return to its 4.5 to 6.5 per cent target this
year, but also dashed any lingering speculation of a rate reduction at
yesterday's council meeting.
The Bundesbank's council lowered the central bank's M3 target range for 1994
to 4 to 6 per cent. This had been widely expected and had little market
impact.
Disappointment that the Bundesbank did not cut rates sent the March
three-month Euromark interest rate contract tumbling by 0.09 point to 94.45.
The French March Pibor contract slid in sympathy, ending at 94.16, down 0.09
point from Wednesday's close. The French franc finished at FFr3.415 to the
D-Mark, compared with FFr3.418 on Wednesday.
The Bank of France left interest rates unchanged at its latest open-market
operation, where it drained FFr9.2bn of liquidity. Its five to 10-day rate
currently stands at 7 per cent, while the intervention rate is 6.2 per cent.
The D-Mark also firmed against the Belgian franc, which fell to BFr20.88,
down from BFr20.86. The Italian lira closed at L987.4 to the D-Mark, down
from L987.0 the previous day. The Danish krone ended at DKr3.912 to the
D-Mark, up from DKr3.923 on Wednesday.
The dollar fell to around DM1.7080, recovered during midday but slipped
towards the close on late profit-taking. It ended at DM1.7085, down from
Wednesday's DM1.7160.
It also slipped against the yen on November trade data showing that the US
trade gap with Japan reached a seven-year high at Dollars 6.1bn. It ended at
Y109.75, up from Y109.65 but off an earlier high of Y110.05.
In New York the dollar closed at DM1.7093 and Y109.55.
Although German interest rates remained on hold, Austria and Switzerland
lowered theirs.
Early in the day, the Swiss National Bank reduced its discount rate by 1/4
percentage point to 4.25 per cent, explaining that the cut took account of
interest rate developments in the markets. However, it stressed there was
only limited room for further interest rate declines.
Immediately after the announcement, the Swiss franc declined to SFr0.859 to
the D-Mark, but it recouped its loss to close at SFr0.853, up from SFr0.855
at Wednesday's close.
'The market is taking the view that the relative interest-rate differential
will move in favour of the Swiss franc,' said Mr Adrian Cunningham, senior
currency analyst at UBS. He feels that the Swiss central bank may shave
another 75 basis points off rates as Swiss inflation continues to ease,
while he expects the German discount rate to fall by around 175 basis points
next year.
The Austrian National Bank announced a 10 basis-point cut in its Gomex
open-market intervention rate to 5.70 per cent, effective today. Earlier
this week a central bank official indicated it would continue cutting
interest rates autonomously if it had room for manoeuvre.
Austria has cut its rates several times in recent months, helped by the
recent strength of the schilling, which on Tuesday was fixed at its highest
level this year against the D-Mark at Ats703.05 per 100 D-Marks, but
yesterday finished at Ats703.15.
The sterling money market was slightly more relaxed, helped by the smaller
liquidity shortage and waning rate-cut expectations.
The Bank of England initially announced a shortage of Pounds 1.5bn, but
later revised that to Pounds 1.1bn. That compares with a Pounds 2.65bn
shortage on Wednesday. In early operations the Bank purchased bills
totalling Pounds 488m for resale to the market on January 7 at 5 13/32 per
cent. In further operations it bought Pounds 58m of bills, followed by late
assistance of around Pounds 510m.
'We have had a terribly tight week, but things should start easing off a
little into the Christmas period,' said a senior money dealer. He added that
the Bank of England had kept the market tight to indicate that there would
be no near-term cut in interest rates. 'Now, all the speculation for rate
cuts this year has gone, which is a reason for the Bank to be a bit less
tight.'
The March short sterling contract slipped by 0.04 point to 94.80 after
sliding by 0.09 point on Wednesday.
Early in the day, the pound firmed briefly to a high of DM2.5478 on the back
of a stronger than expected decline in UK unemployment, but it slipped back
to finish at DM2.5450, unchanged from the previous day. Against the dollar
sterling ended at Dollars 1.4890, compared with Dollars 1.4835 on Wednesday.
