FT  17 DEC 93 / UK Company News: PSB's counter bid intensifies the battle
for control of ICD
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE battle for control of International Communications &amp; Data intensified
yesterday with a counter, though unquantified, bid for the marketing
services company
PSB Group, a direct marketing concern which claims to control 23.6 per cent
of ICD's voting rights, said it would set a price once it was given access
to ICD's books.
The first bid, from IMC Industries and its supporters, was forced into a 9
1/2 p a share offer for the company on December 8, although the USM-quoted
soft drinks and leisure company said it did not wish to gain ICD.
Mr David Cicurel, full time executive chairman of IMC and a big shareholder
in the company, obtained for IMC an option to subscribe for 6.95m shares at
7p as payment for his services as ICD's chairman.
IMC exercised its option, triggering a mandatory takeover bid under the
takeover code. IMC was a reluctant bidder and pitched its offer at the
lowest price permitted under the takeover code.
IMC exercised the option to support the ICD board in its battle with PSB,
which has been seeking control of ICD for about three months.
The option gave IMC a 10.6 per cent stake in ICD. The company and its
supporters now claim to hold about 40 per cent.
At a special meeting held on December 9 ICD shareholders defeated all
resolutions put forward by PSB, which requisitioned the meeting for the
removal of a majority of the existing directors and their replacement by PSB
nominees.
</TEXT>
