<DATE>931217
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / M&amp;G surges as recovery plays pay off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in M&amp;G jumped 30p to 995p yesterday as the fund management group
announced a 36 per cent increase in its final dividend for the year to
September 30. Full-year pre-tax profits advanced 29 per cent from Pounds
39.4m to Pounds 50.9m.
Funds under management rose 45 per cent, helped by buoyant stock markets and
a strong improvement in the group's relative investment performance. M&amp;G
follows a 'value investing' style - looking for shares with artificially
depressed prices - which tends to suffer during recessions, but performs
very well in periods of recovery.
The group's sales of unit trusts (sales minus redemptions) were just Pounds
92m for the year to September 30, against an industry total of more than
Pounds 7bn. Mr Peter Emms, marketing director, said the trust traditionally
did not attract a large share of institutional unit trust sales, nor did it
offer a high income fund.
Some unit trust launches have offered yields as high as 10 per cent and have
been very successful. But Mr Paddy Linaker, group managing director, did not
feel that such products were appropriate for M&amp;G clients. He warned of the
problems unit trust groups faced in the 1970s, when 'withdrawal plans' led
to the erosion of investors' capital in the 1973-74 bear market.
M&amp;G's sales showed signs of improvement in the second half and all four of
its UK equity income funds are in the top 10 per cent of the sector over the
year to September 1. It has more Personal Equity Plan accounts than any
other UK company.
At September 30, unit trust funds under management were Pounds 6.32bn
(Pounds 4.15bn); investment trusts were Pounds 662m (Pounds 456m); life and
pension funds were Pounds 2.14bn (Pounds 1.55bn); and institutional investor
clients were Pounds 3.34bn (Pounds 2.45bn). Total funds under management
were Pounds 12.46bn (Pounds 8.59bn), or Pounds 10.56bn after allowing for
double counting.
Revenue from investment management was Pounds 63.7m (Pounds 59.4m).
Marketing and commissions expenditure was Pounds 13.17m, down from Pounds
18.53m in 1991-92 when the company launched two investment trusts.
Administration expenditure was Pounds 18.6m (Pounds 17.9m).
The group's insurance activities contributed Pounds 12.69m (Pounds 10.19m).
The accounting treatment of this business will change this year to reflect
the EC Insurance Accounts Directive.
The final dividend is increased from 11p to 15p, making a total of 25p,
against 20p. Earnings per share rose from 36.4p to 47.8p.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
