<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Job cuts herald shake-up at Owners Abroad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Francis Baron, new chief executive of holiday company Owners Abroad,
yesterday announced the redundancy of 260 management and support staff and
said he was conducting a review that could change the group's name.
Mr Baron, who took charge of Owners Abroad last month, said the group had
little idea under its previous management of how profitable it was. He added
that its branding and marketing strategy had been incoherent. The defence
documents it published to fight off a takeover by its rival Airtours earlier
this year had 'lacked conviction'.
Mr Baron, a former television executive, replaced Mr Howard Klein, the
former chairman and chief executive, who announced his resignation last
July.
Mr Klein left after the group announced that full-year profits this year
were likely to be half that of market expectations. Mr Baron said that while
the group had been producing large amounts of data, there was no system to
ensure this reached directors in a form that would enable them to assess the
company's performance.
Mr Baron said yesterday's redundancies, accompanied by a restructuring were
the first part of a three-phase plan to restore the group's fortunes.
The restructuring will eliminate four levels of management. General managers
and finance directors of subsidiary companies are leaving. The post of
managing director of tour operating is being abolished and Mr Dermot
Blastland, the current incumbent, is being reassigned to work on a special
project for Mr Baron. Mr Baron would not describe the project.
The second phase of the plan, which Mr Baron hoped to complete by the end of
February, would improve information systems.
The third phase will develop a marketing and branding strategy by the end of
March.
Mr Baron said: 'Everything is up for grabs, including the corporate name.'
Airtours is renaming its Pickfords Travel and Hogg Robinson retail chains.
All 550 shops will be called Going Places. Airtours intends to complete the
rebranding by Christmas.
</TEXT>
