<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Gore hits at IMF over plight of Russia's jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Al Gore, the US vice-president, criticised the International Monetary
Fund yesterday for insensitivity to the plight of the unemployed in Russia,
foreshadowing a possible shift in western policy on helping the country's
economy.
Mr Gore said the effect of huge defence budget cuts on communities dependent
on defence production had been 'devastating'.
He criticised western countries for not waking up to Russia's problems.
'Every country with representatives on the IMF board has been slow to
recognise the hardship caused by some of what has been done in the past.
That may cause a diplomatic incident, but I don't care.'
The IMF was supposed to grant at least Dollars 3bn (Pounds 2bn) in the
current year to assist reform. Only Dollars 1.5bn has been given and there
are doubts if the second tranche will be released.
The IMF has complained that successive Russian governments have not
curtailed the budget deficit and brought inflation down to 5 per cent a
month. Meeting these criteria would mean choking off credits to already
shaky Russian enterprises, causing mass unemployment.
Mr Gore said that 'in circumstances where there is a great deal of economic
suffering and when the world does not pay too much attention to that, then
people become vulnerable to demagoguery'. This was endorsed by Mr Viktor
Chernomyrdin, the Russian prime minister, who said it was in the defence
industries where 'the highest intellectual strength is concentrated, and we
cannot shut them down'.
The neo-fascist Liberal Democratic party swept the board in Sunday's
election in that part of parliament chosen according to party lists. Senior
international financial officials now believe western aid strategies for
Russia will change as a new government reins back the speed of reforms.
Reuter in Washington reports: Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state,
said last night the US would go on supporting Russian reformers. In a TV
interview he said the reformers had needed a 'wake-up call' and should now
build coalitions.
Between extremes, Page 3
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
