<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Observer: England's own goal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
So you thought Graham Taylor was to blame for failing to get the England
football team into next year's World Cup. Wrong. The reason is much more
simple - it's all the fault of the free market.
At least that's the verdict of the left-leaning Institute for Public Policy
Research. Perhaps in an effort to improve its credibility among its
supporters on the terraces, it has produced a report on the decline of the
national game.
Too-high ticket prices, fixture schedules dictated by TV companies, the
decline of the small clubs are all the inevitable product of a system that
leaves clubs, players and television fighting their own corner, says the
think-tank.
'Free market policies have ruined our national economy. Now they threaten
our national game,' argue Dan Corry and Paul Williamson. What the game needs
is a 'dose of national planning'. Sounds familiar.
</TEXT>
