<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Arts: The Arts Council tries to keep things sweet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
England's arts companies discovered yesterday how much subsidy they will
receive from the Arts Council in 1994-95 - and for most of them the news was
better than anticipated. Despite receiving a cut of Pounds 3.2m, or 1.7 per
cent, in its grant from the government, the council, with its usual sleight
of hand, has given most of its clients same again funding next year.
So Covent Garden (which still takes in Birmingham Royal Ballet) is frozen at
Pounds 19.5m; the ENO at Pounds 11.65m; the National Theatre at Pounds
11.16m; and the RSC at Pounds 8.47m. Since all these companies must have
been planning on a small reduction in grant they should be marginally
relieved. It is the same across the board. The South Bank Centre gets Pounds
13.4m; English National Ballet Pounds 3.6m; Manchester Royal Exchange Pounds
1.3m; Opera North, Pounds 3.8m, and on and on.
There are a few rogue payments. Following through its declared, and
unpopular, aim of boosting contemporary dance and the visual arts, the
council has given Dance Umbrella a 20 per cent uplift to Pounds 175,000;
Rambert gets 35 per cent more at Pounds 1.2m; and Shobana Jeyasingh, flush
with Pounds 100,000 as the Prudential Awards winner, enjoys 34 per cent more
from the council at Pounds 170,000. Michael Clark receives his first Pounds
100,000.
In the visual arts, the Whitechapel has a 6.8 per cent improvement to Pounds
471,000; the Photographers Gallery almost a 13 per cent uplift at Pounds
352,000; and the Serpentine, which is threatened with an outrageous increase
in its rent from the Royal Parks, is bolstered with almost 9 per cent more,
at Pounds 248,000.
There is the odd casualty: principally Glyndebourne Touring, and the
Regional Arts Boards, which fund thousands of small arts groups, are
suffering a reduction in grants of up to 4.5 per cent. But the council has
done its bit to keep the arts going through 1994 when falling box office
income, reduced sponsorship and squeezed local authority funding will make
survival difficult.
The council found the money by cutting Pounds 2m from its Pounds 14m budget
for new projects and schemes, especially in the theatre. This is bad news
for touring drama companies, many of which might now close. As secretary
general Anthony Everitt said yesterday, 'the aim is to protect the basic
infra-structure of arts organisations throughout the country'.
By this clever package the council has gone a little way towards recovering
some of the massive loss of face and confidence it suffered through its
mishandling of the funding of the London orchestras. On Wednesday it
confirmed that all four would receive virtually identical grants next year -
a complete climbdown from its aim to axe two and create two super
orchestras.
</TEXT>
