<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hugh Thompson and Phil Loftus, two London paparazzi, are the subject of
today's Short Stories (8.00 C4). They are the ones who got the photograph of
Joan Collins looking dowdy in a head scarf, a picture which earned them
Pounds 8,000. But since they have to turn up just after first light to get a
front row spot for an evening premiere, perhaps the job is not quite the
doddle it may appear.
There was something uniquely charming about the series A Victorian Kitchen
Garden. BBC2's attempt to keep the bandwagon rolling with The Wartime
Kitchen And Garden is nowhere near as successful. It has its moments, but
feels contrived, and where the previous series was concerned with an age
that is entirely lost, the present series is about a period which millions
still remember (8.30 BBC2). All Or Nothing At All is a cut above the sort of
drama we are coming to expect from ITV. Hugh Laurie, normally seen in
partnership with Stephen Fry, is impressive as a compulsive gambler who
longs to make all his friends happy by earning them a fortune (9.00 ITV).
</TEXT>
