<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Littlechild pegs nuclear levy at 10%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The fossil-fuel levy, the surcharge on electricity bills in England and
Wales which subsidises the nuclear power industry and renewable energy, is
to be held at 10 per cent for a further 12 months to avoid another row over
rising fuel bills.
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity regulator who sets the levy
each year, said he considered this level to be the minimum necessary to
raise the required Pounds 1.3bn a year.
In the past Prof Littlechild said he thought the levy should come down each
year. Last year he cut it from 11 per cent. Nuclear Electric, the
state-owned power utility which receives most of the levy proceeds, is also
keen to see it come down to reinforce its claim that nuclear power can
operate commercially.
Last year's cut, however, meant that the levy did not raise enough to cover
subsidies. It should have gone up next year to recover the shortfall and
Prof Littlechild is believed to have proposed an increase to the government.
But the Department of Trade and Industry, shaken by the row over the
decision to impose value added tax on home-heating fuels, is said to have
rejected his proposal and told him to freeze it for another year.
Mr John Collier, chairman of Nuclear Electric, last night welcomed the
freeze. 'Nuclear Electric gets less income from the levy in real terms each
year, and we are firmly on course to be profitable before taking account of
the levy within two years,' he said.
The government is shortly to conduct a review of the future of nuclear power
in the UK, in which the size of the levy is likely to be closely
scrutinised. Ideally, the nuclear industry would have liked to see the levy
come down again to drive home the message that its finances are improving,
but in the circumstances a freeze is the best it can hope for.
Prof Littlechild said the 10 per cent rate 'will apply until any further
change in the rate is introduced. Barring unforeseen circumstances, I expect
the 10 per cent rate to apply for at least 12 months from April 1 1994.'
Prof Littlechild yesterday rejected an appeal by large energy users against
reforms in the wholesale power pool, Michael Smith writes.
Large users say the reforms miss an opportunity for significant change.
Imperial Chemical Industries, one of the complainants, said the reforms
proposed had been universally rejected by large users. It was 'yet another
example of customer's interest not being taken seriously'.
Under the proposed reform the pool is to introduce a system known as
demand-side bidding through which large customers can agree to reduce
consumption if the price goes above a certain level.
This is expected by the pool to lead to average price cuts of about 1.5 per
cent.
ICI and other companies want demand-side bidding, but said the system did
not go far enough in addressing their needs. They wanted a system which
provided more incentive to cut consumption.
Unlike the majority of electricity consumers, some intensive users of
electricity have had to pay considerably more for electricity since
privatisation.
In rejecting the appeal, Prof Littlechild asked the pool to give careful
thought to introducing the system and suggested a three-month trial.
ICI said the system would bring no benefit to customers.
The pool's reform had been due for implementation in October, but is now
likely to be introduced early next year.
</TEXT>
