<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Power station clean-up begins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Power, the electricity generator, took formal receipt yesterday of
the first two of six units which will significantly reduce the amount of
sulphur dioxide it emits from its Drax power station in North Yorkshire,
Michael Smith writes.
Babcock Energy, part of Babcock International, handed over the two flue-gas
desulphurisation (FGD) units a day early after five years' work on the
project. Work on the remaining four units at National Power's largest power
station is expected to be completed by the spring of 1996.
The project, which is costing National Power Pounds 680m, is one of the
world's largest environmental clean-up projects. PowerGen is installing
another set of FGD units at its coal power station in Ratcliffe,
Nottingham-shire.
The high cost of installation makes it unlikely that FGD units will be built
at other coal-fired power stations in the UK. The generators are more likely
to reduce the amount of coal burnt at the stations as the amount of
gas-fired generation increases.
The FGD process at Drax uses large quantities of limestone which contains
alkaline calcium carbonate. This 'captures' the sulpur dioxide in the flue
gas and ends up as gypsum, which can be used in construction.
</TEXT>
