<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Profit not the main factor in Thorp go-ahead: Bronwen Maddox
examines the government's reasons for granting a licence to the reprocessing
plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ministers have made clear that Thorp's profitability was not a central
concern in their decision to give the nuclear reprocessing plant the
go-ahead, even though British Nuclear Fuels, the plant's owner, is a
state-owned company.
That is one of the most startling admissions in the 73-page document,
published on Wednesday, setting out the government's reasons for granting
BNF its licence.
The report's analysis of the economic case for Thorp, one of the central
questions raised in this autumn's public consultation, is particularly
flimsy. It says many of the 42,500 responses to the consultation - 63 per
cent of which opposed Thorp - criticised BNF's claim that Thorp would earn
Pounds 900m for the UK in its first 10 years.
One of the critics' main concerns is that Thorp's customers may try to pull
out of their contracts, undermining the plant's profitability. Reprocessing
extracts re-usable uranium and plutonium from used nuclear-reactor fuel.
Since construction of Thorp was given the go-ahead in 1977, the price of
uranium has fallen and fears about proliferation of plutonium weapons
capability have risen. Ministers say they accept 'circumstances have
changed' but say 'the contractual arrangements between BNF and its customers
are the best and clearest evidence of the utility of reprocessing and
Thorp'.
In a phrase which may prove a hostage to fortune, ministers say they 'are
not persuaded that so much weight should be placed on calculations relating
to BNF's profitability'. Instead they conclude: 'While it is important that
BNF should have the resources to be able to fulfil its financial and
environmental obligations, this does not depend on any part-icular level of
profitability'.
Ministers have also noted, however, that BNF's shareholder is the state. The
report does not examine whether, even if Thorp is profitable, alternative
disposal methods might be more profitable when considered from the UK's
perspective, including that of Nuclear Electric and Scottish Nuclear, its UK
customers.
Wider diplomatic questions have also been dismissed. Ministers say they are
convinced that agreed procedures for guarding plutonium at every stage are
'satisfactory'.
The document gives the impression that ministers found that to license the
Pounds 2.8bn plant was less politically troublesome than to scrap it, almost
regardless of the merits of the economic arguments.
The granting of the licence does not jeopardise relations with foreign
governments, particularly the Japanese, and it provides jobs in a depressed
part of the UK.
Perhaps most important, it avoids the embarrassment of making Thorp, in
environmentalists' words, 'Britain's biggest white elephant'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Nuclear Fuels.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2819 Industrial Inorganic Chemicals, NEC.
    P4911 Electric Services.
</IN>
<XX>
