<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / State spending pushes up PSBR
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Higher government spending, compared with a year ago, pushed up the public
sector borrowing requirement to Pounds 3.13bn last month, the Treasury said
yesterday.
In the first eight months of the financial year overall government borrowing
totalled Pounds 30bn, compared with Pounds 22bn in the corresponding period
last year.
Local authorities repaid Pounds 1.21bn of debt in November, however,
continuing their recent record of reducing borrowings.
The figures underline how the recession has increased borrowing, partly
because higher unemployment has pushed up social security spending and lower
growth has held down tax revenues.
Spending by central government departments, combined with interest payments
and taking into account privatisation proceeds, came to Pounds 21.5bn last
month. This compares with Pounds 21.32bn in October and Pounds 19.93bn in
November last year.
Central government revenues held up fairly well last month, totalling Pounds
17.14bn, after Pounds 18.1bn in October and Pounds 16.92bn in November 1992.
Inland Revenue receipts were relatively buoyant at Pounds 4.06bn last month,
after Pounds 3.85bn in the same month last year.
The PSBR, which takes into account the gap between spending and revenues for
both central and local government, was Pounds 2.69bn in October and Pounds
2.06bn in the previous November. In the last financial year the deficit came
to Pounds 36.68bn. The Treasury's forecast in last month's Budget puts the
1993-94 deficit at Pounds 49.8bn.
November was the fourth successive month in which local authorities repaid
debt. In November last year they repaid Pounds 570m. So far this financial
year local authorities have repaid a net Pounds 3bn, compared with
repayments of Pounds 7.1bn in the equivalent period of 1992-93.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
