<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Vacancy counting system may alter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Department of Employment statisticians are considering a move to a more
accurate measure for the number of job vacancies in the economy, which are
substantially understated by the current method.
The November vacancy figure announced yesterday was 140,900 - 6,500 up on
the previous month, 24,000 up on a year before and the highest since October
1990. But most labour market analysts believe that the real figure could be
three or four times more.
The present figure counts vacancies notified to Jobcentres, but many
vacancies are advertised in newspapers or through private employment
agencies. The largest single way in which vacancies are communicated is by
word of mouth.
Mr Peter Stibbard, director of statistics at the employment department, said
it would be difficult to capture vacancies that never enter the public
domain, but information from newspapers and employment agencies could be
used.
The new system was likely to establish an index of the change in vacancies
rather than a new number. Mr Stibbard added: 'We want to establish a rapidly
available barometer of the vacancy position in the labour market.' Ministers
have not yet discussed the proposal but are unlikely to oppose it. The
department already does occasional spot checks of vacancies using a broader
measure than Jobcentre notifications. It found that in some areas the number
is up to three times higher.
The seasonally adjusted official figure for the inflow of vacancies now
stands at 199,500, the highest figure since June 1990. Jobcentre placings of
150,400 are also at the highest level since March 1990.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
