<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Bank 'should seek to achieve price stability'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The influential cross-party Commons Treasury and civil service committee
yesterday said the Bank of England should have greater autonomy over
monetary policy but be made more accountable to parliament.
The committee agreed by a 9-1 majority, with Ms Diane Abbott, the Labour MP
for Hackney North dissenting, that the Bank of England Act should be amended
so that the primary objective of the Bank would be to 'achieve and maintain'
price stability.
Publication of the committee's keenly awaited report gave an immediate boost
to supporters of more autonomy for the Bank. The Commons will debate the
commit-tee's proposals early next year.
Mr Nicholas Budgen, the Conservative MP for Wolverhampton South-West and a
committee member, is preparing a private member's bill, based on the
committee's recommendations, that will be given its second reading on
January 28.
The committee's report recommended that the Bank should be operationally
responsible for achieving stable prices, a move that would transfer power to
change interest rates from the Treasury to the Bank.
The committee said that the government and Bank should agree publicly stated
targets for price stability which would be open to debate in parliament. The
targets, it said, should be set in the light of monetary and other
indicators 'including the extent of spare capacity in the economy and the
overall stance of fiscal policy'. It said the Bank should be made far more
accountable to parliament through an annual report, which would be debated
in the Commons, and through appearances of the governor before the Treasury
committee.
The committee said its proposals would require changes in the Bank,
including the creation of 'a strong and independent monetary policy
committee' comprising the governor, the deputy governor and other executive
directors.
It said, however, that the government should have power to override the
Bank's objective of price stability temporarily and in exceptional
circumstances.
The committee gave lukewarm support for the Bank retaining its role as
supervisor of the UK banking industry.
It said this position would need to be reviewed if there were to be a
complete reorganisation of banking and financial services regulation.
The committee plans to investigate supervision under the Financial Services
Act in the new year. It will also look into recent revelations on the
inappropriate selling of private pension schemes.
The committee emphasised the importance of greater transparency in monetary
policy. It recommended publication, after a lag, of the minutes of existing
monthly meetings between the chancellor and Bank governor and said the
minutes of the proposed monetary policy committee should also be published
after an interval.
The Bank welcomed the report, and a spokesman pointed out that Mr Eddie
George, its governor, believed institutional changes such as those proposed
would help it to achieve price stability.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said he had an open mind. 'I will give it
careful consideration,' he said in a Commons reply. 'We need further
discussion and debate. I have a feeling that at the moment it has become
something of a fashionable cause.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P6011 Federal Reserve Banks.
    P6021 National Commercial Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
