<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / MP raps MMC on 'perverse' rulings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chairman of the Commons all-party Treasury committee has tabled an
early-day motion criticising recent recommendations of the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission for failing to uphold the public interest, Roland Rudd
writes.
Mr John Watts, the Conservative chairman, yesterday attacked what he called
the commission's recent 'perverse' ruling that the so-called 'complex
monopoly' created by the perfume industry was not against the public
interest.
His motion, which has been signed by members of all three main parties,
calls on the commission 'to be fearless in eliminating anti-competitive
behaviour in the distribution of consumer products'.
Mr Watts said he had in mind the commission's investigation into competition
in the Pounds 800m-a-year ice-cream market.
The commission is examining the widespread practice among manufacturers of
supplying freezer cabinets free of charge to small retail outlets, on
condition that the cabinets are not used to stock competitors' products.
Mr Watts singled out Walls, part of the Anglo-Dutch Unilever group, as an
example of an ice-cream maker which was using its muscle as a freezer
supplier to discourage small retailers from supplying other ice creams.
Mars, the US-owned food manufacturer, has repeatedly challenged Unilever's
domination of the European ice-cream market in Brussels and in national
courts. It started making ice-cream versions of its chocolate bars in 1989
and now has about 10 per cent of UK impulse sales, which are the
fastest-growing part of the market.
The all-party early-day motion on the commission says it 'regrets that a
number of recent MMC recommendations have favoured current market structure
at the expense of the consumer interest and therefore the public interest'.
Mr Malcolm Bruce, Liberal Democrat industry spokesman, who signed the
motion, said: 'This is a direct message to the MMC that they are too
cautious and too conservative.'
</TEXT>
