<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Industrial orders 'improved'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Order books in manufacturing have improved but expectations about output
have slipped, says a Confederation of British Industry survey published
today.
Export orders are still ranked below normal by a third of companies, but are
still at their highest level for six months.
Inflationary pressures continue to be extremely weak, with more
manufacturers expecting to cut domestic prices in the next four months than
to raise them.
The results from the CBI's latest poll of manufacturers indicate that output
should continue its recent patchy rise in the next few months.
The survey covered 1,383 companies across 50 industries. It was conducted
between November 26 and December 14, with most of the replies coming after
the Budget.
Overall orders covering both the UK and export markets were ranked below
normal by 37 per cent of companies, with 18 per cent saying they were above
normal.
The difference between the two readings of 19 percentage points establishes
an improving trend compared with the negative balances of 23 points and 31
points in the CBI's November and October surveys.
A balance of 9 percentage points of companies said output volumes were
likely to rise in the next four months. The balance was 12 points last month
and 8 points in October. This month's survey is the twelfth in a row to
point to higher output volumes.
Although considered unsatisfactory by most companies, the export outlook
improved on November, with a negative balance of 14 points of companies
saying export order books are below normal. This is the best result since
the negative balance of 10 points recorded in June.
</TEXT>
