<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Fiat to stop selling Lancia cars
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Fiat is to stop selling its Lancia cars in the UK and phase out production
of right-hand drive Lancia models.
The decision marks the defeat of Fiat's decade-long struggle to revive the
marque's fortunes in the UK, after sales were devastated by a controversy
over rusting at the end of the 1970s.
At their peak in 1978 Lancia sales reached 11,800. But allegations a year
later of excessive rust in the then best-selling Beta model badly damaged
the marque's reputation, in spite of Fiat buying back cars from dissatisfied
owners.
Since then sales have declined inexorably. In 1989 - the record year for
total car sales - they were down to just over 3,000. Last year they totalled
only 701, and up to last night 569 had been sold this year.
Fiat Auto (UK), the Fiat parent, said last night that it was contacting all
Lancia owners to assure them of continuing service, parts and warranty
assistance.
Lancia owners with vehicles registered since August 1990 are also being
issued with a coupon worth up to Pounds 1,600, redeemable on either a new
Fiat or Alfa Romeo, another marque owned by the Fiat group.
Most of the 46 Lancia dealers, which are on 12-month contracts, have a dual
franchise with Fiat, whose own sales have risen by more than one third, from
31,000 last year to 42,000 so far this year. Some dealers will be offered
the Alfa Romeo franchise as a Lancia substitute.
Before the rust scare the UK was Lancia's largest right-hand drive market.
Its collapse has significantly reduced the incentive for Fiat to keep
right-hand drive cars in production. The Irish Republic, New Zealand, Hong
Kong, Singapore, Cyprus and some African and Pacific rim markets have
accounted for a small volume of sales but future Lancias will not be
engineered for such markets.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Fiat.
    Fiat Auto (UK).
</CO>
<XX>
