<DATE>931217
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Building societies urged to merge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Medium-size building societies face the choice of merging with each other or
being taken over and - probably - eliminated.
That is the message of a study published today by Morgan Grenfell, the
merchant bank, which says that medium-size building societies need to
achieve cost savings and to form their own regional branch networks to
enable them to compete more effectively with the banks.
The report also argues that larger societies need to concentrate on selling
services and products to their savers rather than to borrowers, where the
emphasis has been so far.
The paper comes against the background of the abandonment in October of the
merger plans of the Leeds Permanent building society, the fifth largest, and
the National &amp; Provincial, the eighth largest.
It highlights the effectiveness for larger societies of mergers, where they
take over a small society and close its head office and most branches, over
combinations between the largest societies.
While banks have cut their staff numbers by 10 per cent since 1989,
societies' staff numbers have risen by 6 per cent, and the falls in
societies' cost-to-income ratios have come largely from higher income rather
than lower costs.
When serious competition from the retail banks intensifies, societies will
be unable to rely on wider margins to maintain profits at an acceptable
level, and will need to cut costs, the paper says.
But whereas banks can cut branches and transfer business to an alternative
convenient for the customer, an individual society will almost certainly not
be in that position - in total, societies have only half the number of
branches that banks have.
On savings, the study recognises societies' concern that they may be
'cannibalising' the retail savings base they need to support their mortgage
lending, by selling their investors other products such as Peps or unit
trusts.
It argues, however, that unless they offer such services, savers will seek
them elsewhere, and societies will find they are excluded from a growing
area of the market.
It is particularly important for a society to own the supplier, rather than
acting as agent for another institution, which can then build its own
relationship with the investor.
Building Societies - Diversification and Cost Cutting to Combat Declining
Business. Morgan Grenfell, 23 Gt Winchester St, London, EC2P 2AX. Pounds 75.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
