<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Parental payments to students decrease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The introduction of student loans has allowed a cut in the contributions
which parents make towards university education, according to a survey
published yesterday by the Department for Education, John Authers writes.
It found the average cost paid by parents fell by 19 per cent between
1988-89 and 1992-93, with 57 per cent of parents paying more than their
formally assessed contribution and 3 per cent paying less. Only 6 per cent
of students' income came from earnings.
Over the period the proportion of students from the 'AB' socio-economic
groups fell from 55 per cent to 49 per cent, which the department
interpreted as evidence that loans had not deterred children of poorer
families from applying to university.
