<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 93 / Securicor beats Group 4 to escort job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Securicor yesterday gained its first stake in the growing penal services
market by winning the contract to provide court-escort services in the
London area.
The five-year contract to handle about 11,000 prisoner movements a month
between prisons, police stations and courts is worth Pounds 96m.
The first private court-escort service, taken over by Group 4 in the east
Midlands, Yorkshire and Humberside region earlier this year, led to a series
of escapes and other incidents in the first weeks of the new operation. As a
result, the Prison Service has decided Securicor will take over the London
service in five stages between next July and July 1995.
Mr Derek Lewis, chief executive of the Prison Service, said Securicor
Custodial Services had won the contract 'against strong competition'. He
said it was evident that privately run escort services reduced duplication,
led to more efficient use of police and prison officers' time, and
represented better value for money for the taxpayer. Transferring the
services to the private sector enabled police and prison officers to
concentrate their skills and energies on the work for which they were
trained.
Securicor will handle all prisoners except those in the highest security
category.
Group 4 was among the unsuccessful bidders for the London contract. The
company remains a strong contender for the contract to manage the new
Doncaster prison. Group 4 already runs Wolds remand prison on Humberside and
winning the Doncaster contract would give the company a basis for building
up a range of privately managed penal services in a single region.
</TEXT>
