FT  17 DEC 93 / Ex-BCCI official denies six charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A former senior employee of the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce
International pleaded not guilty to six charges of fraud at the Old Bailey
yesterday.
Mr Imran Imam, a former official at BCCI's London offices, faces two charges
of conspiring to conceal documents, three of furnishing false information
and one of conspiring to falsify records.
His trial, expected to last between eight and 10 weeks, is set to begin on
April 11 next year. Mr Imam was released on bail with sureties of Pounds
75,000.
Earlier, Judge Pownall QC rejected an application for the prosecution to be
dismissed. Mr Imam had claimed that the Serious Fraud Office had given an
undertaking to the US authorities investigating BCCI that he would not be
prosecuted in the UK.
Mr Imam gave evidence to the US authorities as a witness which was then
passed to the SFO before his arrest.
The judge ruled that the SFO had given no undertaking that Mr Imam would not
be prosecuted.
